{{Other uses|Filament (disambiguation)}}
'''Filamentation''' is the anomalous growth of certain [[bacteria]], such as ''[[E. coli]]'', in which cells continue to elongate but do not divide (no [[septum|septa]] formation). The cells that result from elongation without division have multiple chromosomal copies.<ref>{{citation|authors= Jaimes-Lizcano, Yuly A,, Hunn, Dayton D.,  Papadopoulos, Kyriakos D., 2014. |title= Filamentous Escherichia coli cells swimming in tapered microcapillaries. |publisher= Research in Microbiology 165: 166-174.}}</ref>  Bacterial filamentation is often observed as a result of  bacteria responding to various stresses, including [[DNA damage]] or inhibition of replication. This may happen, for example, while responding to extensive DNA damage through the [[SOS response|SOS response system]]. Nutritional changes may also cause bacterial filamentation. Some of the key genes involved in filamentation in E.coli include ''sulA'' and ''minCD''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jb.asm.org/cgi/content/short/175/4/1118 |title=Cell division inhibitors SulA and MinCD prevent formation of the FtsZ ring. - Bi and Lutkenhaus 175 (4): 1118 |publisher=The Journal of Bacteriology |date=February 1993 |accessdate=2010-09-21}}</ref> The following genes have been connected to virulence using the G. mellonella infection model: BCR1,FLO8, KEM1, SUV3 and TEC1.  These genes are required for [[biofilm]] development from filamentation.<ref>{{citation|authors= Fuchs, Beth Burgwyn et al., 2010.|title=Role of filamentation in Galleria mellonella killing by Candida albicans.|publisher= Microbes and Infection 12: 488-496.}}</ref>  
Filamentation properties are argued to be necessary in virulence.<ref>{{citation|authors= Fuchs, Beth Burgwyn et al., 2010.|title=Role of filamentation in Galleria mellonella killing by Candida albicans.|publisher= Microbes and Infection 12: 488-496.}}</ref> The biofilm of bacteria is also connected to the organism’s virulence. Filamentation is a survival strategy that protects bacteria from stressors such as host effectors and protist predators.<ref>{{citation|authors= Jaimes-Lizcano, Yuly A,, Hunn, Dayton D.,  Papadopoulos, Kyriakos D., 2014. |title= Filamentous Escherichia coli cells swimming in tapered microcapillaries. |publisher= Research in Microbiology 165: 166-174.}}</ref> The strategy of filamentation is known to protect bacteria from antibiotic medicines taken by the host.

